social_posts.post_text:
Obituaries are the worst things to write but there's no avoiding the task when you're the author in the family. 

My mother passed away this weekend and even though I'd known the time was coming, it's still terribly overwhelming and difficult.

I'll be stepping away from socials for the month, maybe longer.

Hi. I'm Kate. It's been awhile. About six months. So here's the quick intro: I write spicy romance and I require three different beverages at all times in order to meet my basic survival needs. Please assure me that I'm not alone in having such complex hydration needs.

I'm wrapping up work on a new project right now. It's a brother's best friend story with some age gap, some enemies who realize they aren't quite enemies, and the wonky small town of Friendship, Rhode Island. Which means Noah and Shay will make an appearance or two. 

I'll be back in a few weeks with a cover, release date, and the blurb ♥️

ps that's iced green tea, sparkling water, and Liquid IV 🥂

Right about this time last summer, I started wondering what would happen if Noah ever stumbled across his fake wife's toy box. 

Then I realized he wouldn't have to stumble because Shay would just drop it and then give him a lesson. Project based learning, baby.

This is all to say that I am extremely fortunate that I get to listen to these wonderings and daydreams.
All the things. Next Friday. Here's what I'll say about it until then: Friendship has never been so hot.

His best friend's little sister is not an option.

No one ever accused Beckett Loew of being the nice Loew brother, especially not Sunny duJardin. 

Stuck back home in the quirky town of Friendship, Rhode Island, Beckett is scrambling to save his family’s oyster bar and take care of his teenage brother. 

He doesn’t have time to deal with the beautiful, sunshine-y owner of the new vegan cafe next door too. 

His best friend’s little sister may be all grown up, but Sunny’s still a distracting pain in his side. 

No one expects much from Sunny duJardin, especially not Beckett Loew. 

She’s not worried about her older brother’s tall, dark, and broody best friend or the battles he insists on waging with her every day. 

She's not the same kid he teased years ago. 

Now, she composts his type for breakfast. 

They’re all wrong for each other. 
Bitter rivals. 
Complete opposites. 
Off limits.

Except they can’t keep their hands off each other. 

They tell themselves it’s nothing more than a steamy summer fling until secrets spill and real trouble comes their way.

🦪 

Some of the tropes you'll find in Shucked:
enemies-to-lovers
grumpy x sunshine
"I am painfully aware of everything you do"
older brother's best friend
small town (with appearances from Shay and Noah)
“who did this to you?”

Content Warnings: Chronic illness (epilepsy), mention of childhood bullying, putting the fun in dysfunctional families, parents who turn into accidental criminals, incarceration, open door spice, happy ever after, no cliffhanger, suspense and moments of peril.

A SNEAK PEEK AT SHUCKED!
He took my hands, pressed them to his chest. Pushed against himself. “Tell me to stop. Please.”
“I’m not going to do that.”
“Sunny, I need you to say it.”
“I won’t.”
“Why the f*** not?”
“Because I don’t want to,” I replied. “And I don’t think you want it either.”

🦪  Shucked is coming August 22! Visit my links to preorder the ebook. Paperback preorders are likely to show up in August and as soon as I have audio info I'm allowed to share, I'll let you know!

He ran a hand down my spine. “You’re not wearing a bra—”
“Why would I torture myself that way?”
“—and that’s doing terrible things to me.”
“Oh, please. It’s not like I have enough going on for it to matter.”
“It matters to me. Everything you do matters to me, in case you haven’t noticed.” He skimmed a hand up my flank and drew his thumb along the underside of my br***t. I tried and failed to withhold a soft gasp. “And believe me when I say I love what you have going on.”

🦪  Shucked is coming August 22!

“I-I should go,” I managed. 
He nodded, his head tucked into the crook of my shoulder as he kissed a tender spot behind my ear. “You keep saying that but I don’t see you leaving.”
“Probably has something to do with the, ah”—I ran a palm over his thick bicep—"very large, very athletic man pinning me to various surfaces.”
He pulled back just far enough to catch my eye. “Is that a compliment?”
“Is that the sort of f thing you need? I would’ve guessed you exist on protein shakes and the bones of those who dare to cross you.”
“If that was the case, I would’ve eaten you weeks ago.”

I knew the town of Friendship when I wrote In a Jam but after writing Shucked, I am ready to move there permanently. Who is with me?

Also: that's probably why the extended epilogue (which is my favorite epilogue ever written, bonus or otherwise) is good and girthy 🩷🩷
The Friendship, RI starter pack definitely needs a Naked koozie. What else do we need?

This book baby is a little more than 2 weeks old and I am in love with all the messages and comments I'm getting about all the little call backs to limes, shenanigans, shambles, the team in DC, and so much more. Did you catch any of my tiny love letters to longtime readers?

And yeah, the book is backwards though I think it's pretty miraculous that I remembered to take this pic at all 🫠
Back at it 🩷 I love that I'm writing autumn again. There is something so delightful and cozy about a pumpkin spiced season. What's your favorite season to read?

Can you believe it's been a whole year since Noah, Shay, and Gennie arrived? I can't either. Thank you for making In a Jam one of my most loved books ever. Everything about this book was a risk for me and I'm still amazed, even a year later, that these characters have found a lasting place in your heart. 

I'm wondering what Gennie would do to celebrate Noah and Shay's first anniversary. That could go a lot of different directions, right? What do you think?

In case you missed it, In a Jam is available in a lot of ways, all accessible in my profile:

🍓 Ebook
🍓 Paperback
🍓 Audio narrated by Jason Clarke and Kit Swann
🍓 Translated into Dutch, Hebrew, Turkish, Spanish (coming soon), and a few others I'm waiting on the go-ahead to announce!
🍓 Merch coming very soon! It's so gorgeous!
🍓 Special, all-new book box collaboration on its way!

I've been working on a book set in autumn/winter in Boston though I keep wondering whether I could get away with inventing a reason for these characters to hit up a Friendship festival. 

If you had to choose one festival, would it be craft beers and corgis (from Shucked) or the harvest festival (aka the night of many spicy things for Shay and Noah)?

I don't think jam was part of Shay's original plan but I think we can agree it worked out pretty well for her in the end. 

What are you reading this weekend? I just finished Deal with the Devil by @elizabethoroark and now I'm listening to Fastest Way to Fall by @nicwillwrites and eyeball reading Love on the Byline by @xioaxelrod -- all sensational.

They grow up so fast!

In some ways, it feels like this book has been out in the world for decades. Lifetimes.  But in many others, it feels like yesterday that I was writing bits of this story between figuring out how to care for a newborn baby and working the dream job that was sucking my soul out by the day. 

I remember stopping at a certain point (as anyone who has read this knows, it's an early point) and having a serious conversation with myself about spice. I honestly didn't know if I could do it. There's a big difference between 🫑 and 🌶. I wasn't sure where I was in the heat levels. 

It sorted itself out. 

In any event, this baby has had a lot of looks over the years but there's something about the yellow that's always said Lauren to me. Which one is your favorite?

I visited a local school today to talk about being an author and it was quite the journey for all involved. The work of writing often seems difficult to encapsulate (honestly, it's just the entirety of the Rilo Kiley song "A Better Son/Daughter" but I'm not telling kids that) so I brought props. Lots of props. 

My id list notebook, filled with pages of names and titles and random moments to write, along with the first inklings of books.

The notebook filled with Sara and Sebastian, in which the first 10 pages are research about stars and iron and trauma surgery.

The first notebook, the one that starts with a list of names (Patrick, Shannon, Matt, Sam, Riley but his name wasn't originally Riley, Erin) and their birthdays.

My graph paper word count tracker. My post-it plotting plans.  My post-it note chapter plans. My four-month plans.

And a few books. Proof that it all turned into something real. 

The best part was talking to kids struggling to make their own stories sound the way they want or running up against a wall of perfectionism because there is nowhere I sympathize more than with those struggles.

"...is to f**k you on the floor."

Happy Bookiversary to my original grumpy boss Patrick Walsh and his black cat (and much younger) apprentice Andy Asani. This is one of my favorite books ever 🖤

Seems like a great day to mention some of my favorite reads so far this year. 

Before I Let Go by Kennedy Ryan. I'll never not be obsessed with this audio. I need to set aside time to explain to you in extraordinary detail why this whole book is so immensely good because it really, really is. I'm ready to throw elbows for an early look at the next book in the series.

The Marriage Game by Sara Desai. I'm particularly fond of the one-star review that starts “this book is extremely s*x driven”

If Shakespeare Were an Auntie series by Nisha Sharma. I mentioned this in my Stories but I haven't given a proper rec yet & I'll need a minute to really unpack all my thoughts about this series because there's so much there. If the dysfunctional-complicated family element of The Walshes or Santillians works for you, you'll love this series.

Love on the Byline by Xio Axelrod. I've read so many journalist/magazine writer books this year and this is one of the best. Xio writes a damn good book.

Forget Me Not by Julie Soto. Easily one of my favorites of 2023. It's just so soft & lovely. I will never not adore a story told in alternating timelines.

The Kings of Sin series by Ana Huang. Pure, decadent escapism. In KU.

The Gridiron Series by Jen Frederick. The first in this series, Sacked, is one of my all-time favorite reads. It features an inexperienced footballer, a football-loving love interest, and a very memorable supporting cast. In KU!

The Playbook Series by Alexa Martin. These books are smart, funny, & spicy.

Eastside Brewery series by Mia Hopkins. The series follows the Rosas brothers, each at a crossroads in their lives & trying to forge a path forward in a world where their options are limited. I don't think there's anything better than stories where characters find peace and happiness and belonging, all while triumphing over the things (and people and places) that had held them back in the past.

Filthy Rich series by Angelina M. Lopez. There are a lot of things this series does incredibly well but chief among them is the ability to draw strong, powerful, complex female characters and slowly, slowly peel back the layers to show us their soft, vulnerable sides.

Shucked has a new look! 
 
Did I set out with the intention of changing a cover an eye blink after release? Definitely no. Cover design sucks up waaaaay too much of my time.
 
Did I try something new (for me) with the original cover? Yeah, but I'm not mad about it. A ton of time and research went into that original look and it was cute and spanky and of the moment, though, after living with it for a few months, it just didn't feel like me…or Beckett and Sunny. Even though I love the way the artist drew Sunny for the original cover.

There's an ebook look and a paperback look, which isn't always my preference because I enjoy order, but it felt right for this book. Since we don't all have to like the same things in the same ways, it's okay if you prefer the original look. It's okay if you don't like any of them. 
 
Covers are just the energy of the story--which can take many forms. The interior is the emotional experience. 

Anyway! What are you reading this weekend? I'm listening to Daisy Jones and the Six and I have an ARC from Chloe Liese burning up my Kindle.

Happy anniversary to Will and Shannon, two of the most fervently loved characters I've ever written. 

It's funny, actually, since I was convinced right up until publication that everyone would NOT love this book. Shannon is the tough oldest sister, the one who holds it all together, and she never stops being tough. Will is also tough. In some of the same ways but many different ones too. And nothing about her strength threatens his strength, and that's probably my favorite thing about this couple. 

A LOT of readers met me with The Cornerstone, so I'm wondering: is this where you met me? Or a different book?
'tis the season to get snowed in while you're trying to get home for the holidays, and with the guy from work who can't stand you.

'tis the season to inherit your aunt's almost-uninhabitable cottage and try to fix it up while the grouchy tree doctor next door watches and judges, grouchily. And then he shows up, grouchily, when you nearly burn down the house. And he drives you to the lawyer's office to sign your divorce papers, also grouchily. But you're surprised to learn he's not quite so grouchy in bed. 

what are you reading today? I have an early look at Kennedy Ryan's This Could Be Us (so good!) in ebook and I'm finishing Daisy Jones and the Six on audio (also so good!).

'tis the season to marry your high school best friend because your step-grandmother's will requires you to be coupled up in order to inherit the only place that's ever felt like home to you.

What are you hoping you'll find under the tree this year?

Merry Christmas from my bookstack to yours 🩷 

I hope you find a few minutes to sneak away and read. I'm excited to get back to an early peek at This Could Be Us by Kennedy Ryan. What are you reading?

'tis the season to make a crazy New Year's resolution instead of letting your mother run your matchmaking profiles, and end up flashing your hot new neighbor and catching feelings for an emotionally unavailable guy. 

Are you making any resolutions this year?
